<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-29T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-29T23:00:00-05:00" n="244" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d244">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 661.939/3</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_RPS1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-30T12:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">April 30,
                                            1918, noon</hi></date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 30, 10.17 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Referring to your telegram April 25, 5 p.m. There is no change in the
                                embargo matter. The Chinese Government feels embargo is a great
                                detriment but will maintain it for the sake of Allies while they
                                insist. The British and French Governments continue to insist on
                                embargo, Russian Minister believing that export of foodstuffs to
                                regions east of Irkutsk not dangerous but desirable.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_RPS1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>